rces trees provide. In return, animals help with pollination, seed dispersal, and recycling of nutrients. The Hidden Company That Trees Keep blends marvelous storytelling with beautiful illustrations and the latest science to reveal how the lives of trees are intertwined with those of their diverse companions.Features a wealth of richly detailed drawings accompanied by breathtaking images of microscopic landscapes on leaf, bark, and root surfacesIncludes informative fact boxesDraws on new discoveries in biology and natural historyWritten by one of the world’s leading naturalists  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aForest ecology. 0aPlant chemical ecology. 0aPlant-fungus relationships. 0aPlant-soil relationships. 0aTreesxEcology. 0aTrees-Ecology. 7aNATURE / Plants / Trees.2bisacsh  aJames B. Nardi A spectacularly illustrated journey.  aLife from Treetops to Root Tips.  aPrinceton Nature.  aThe Hidden Company That Trees Keep.  aair.  aanimals that live in trees.  aanimals.  abark.  abeautiful book about trees.  abiology.  abirds.  abooks for environmentalists.  abooks for tree lovers.  abreathing clean air.  abreathtaking images.  acarbon dioxide.  aclean air.  aconservation.  adetailed drawings.  aenvironment.  afact boxes.  afacts about trees.  aforests.  agreen energy.  ahiking.  ahow trees benefit.  ainsects.  aleaf scales.  aleaf.  aleaves.  amammals.  amicroscopic landscapes.  anature.  anew discoveries in biology and natural history.  anitrogen.  aoxygen.  apollination.  apollution.  arain forest.  arecycling of nutrients.  aroot surfaces.  aseed dispersal.  asustainaibility.  athe intimate communities that native trees share with animals, insects, fungi, and microbes.  athe life of a tree.  athe visible resources 